Here are both approaches for Shell navigation in .NET MAUI.

**1. Register the route**

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage**

```csharp
// Approach A – pass a simple string ID
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}

// Approach B – pass the full object
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", navParams);
}
```

**3. Receive data in the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A – simple string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, DB, etc.
        }

        // Approach B – full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation** | `GoToAsync($"route?key={val}")` | `GoToAsync("route", Dictionary<string,object>)` |
| **Received as** | `object` (cast to string) | `object` (cast to your type) |
| **Survives URI serialization** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (in-memory only) |
| **Use when** | You can re-fetch from ID | You already have the object and want to avoid an extra lookup |

Both approaches land in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can support them simultaneously as shown above.
